<m0>  In the final week of the legislative session, lawmakers avoid taking a stand on one of the most controversial bills (--) the measure requiring a woman to wait for 24 hours before having an abortion after getting advice on alternatives.<ep>
  The bill has cleared two of the Senate's committees (--) amended to apply to women younger than 18. But it is bottled up in the House, where Health Care Chairman <m0>Ben Graber, <m0>D-Coral Springs, has refused to hear it in his committee. Leaders aren't likely to schedule a full vote on the Senate bill before the session ends.<ep>
  The one option for advocates such as Rep. <m0>Bob Brooks, <m0>R-Winter Park, a physician, is to attempt to amend the measure to another bill on the House floor. Graber says some Republican lawmakers privately have told him that they don't want to see a formal vote on this divisive issue in an election year.<ql>
