<m0>  Watch for a vote on the effort to override Gov. <m0>Lawton Chiles <m0>and repeal Florida's tough anti-tobacco law as soon as Tuesday.<ep>
  Senate President <m0>Jim Scott <m0>said Friday he doubts the Senate will vote on a bill narrowing the scope of Florida's law to cigarettemakers.<ep>
  The bill (S 12) was aimed at ensuring that other businesses aren't vulnerable to lawsuits under the law that Chiles has used to sue tobaccomakers for $420 million a year (--) the estimated cost of smoking-related illnesses suffered by Florida's poor. With this measure dead in the House, said Scott, R-Fort Lauderdale, a Senate vote is a moot point.<ep>
  This was music to the ears of tobacco lobbyists hoping that the bill's failure will lend momentum to their effort to repeal the law. ``I don't see how this can't help the override,'' said lobbyist Guy Spearman, representing The Tobacco Institute.<ql>
