<m0> A legal dispute between the House and the Senate that threatened to derail the effort to redraw the boundaries for a new congressional district in northeast Florida was settled Friday.<ep>
  The House and Senate had disagreed on whether the measure approving a new district for U.S. Rep. <m0>Corrine Brown, <m0>which a federal court ruled is unconstitutional, would have to be a bill or a resolution.<ep>
  Senate President <m0>Jim Scott<m0> said the federal ruling permitted the House and Senate to create the new district through a resolution, which could bypass Gov. <m0>Lawton Chiles <m0>to become law. House Speaker <m0>Peter Wallace, <m0>D-St. Petersburg, said both chambers had to approve a bill that must go to the governor. Chiles sided with the House, saying he would not recognize a new district unless it was approved by a bill.<ep>
  With the Senate primed to pass a resolution redrawing Brown's district, Wallace this week asked the federal court to settle the dispute. The court said the House and Senate should pass a bill.<ql>
